title: Frenchman's Cove, Newfoundland and Labrador
text:
Frenchman's Cove is a town on the west coast of <a href="Burin%20Peninsula">Burin Peninsula</a>, <a href="Newfoundland%20and%20Labrador">Newfoundland and Labrador</a>, Canada. It had a population of 169 in the <a href="Canada%202016%20Census">Canada 2016 Census</a>, a drop from 172 in 2011. The town has been inhabited since before 1836, the earliest known documentation about it, when it appeared in the first Newfoundland Census. According to local folklore and tradition, the first settlers were named Cleuetts and were of French origin. The small-boat inshore fishery was the economic mainstay of the area until the late 1800s when did men went work on the <a href="schooners">schooners</a> operating from <a href="Grand%20Bank">Grand Bank</a>. Residents also grew <a href="turnips">turnips</a>, <a href="cabbages">cabbages</a>, and <a href="potatoes">potatoes</a>, as well as <a href="hay">hay</a> for their <a href="horses">horses</a>, <a href="cattle">cattle</a>, <a href="sheep">sheep</a>, and <a href="chickens">chickens</a>. 
Nearby <a href="Frenchman%27s%20Cove%20Provincial%20Park">Frenchman's Cove Provincial Park</a>, is next to a large <a href="barachois">barachois</a>, sand and mud flats, mixed forest, and <a href="Intertidal_zone">tidal</a> lagoons. Wildlife in the area includes sea and terrestrial birds, including <a href="Canada%20Geese">Canada Geese</a>.
